<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="nginx-configuration">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>devops-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Nginx as high-performance HTTP server, reverse proxy, and load balancer. Key production requirements: TLS 1.2/1.3 only, server_tokens off, security headers, rate limiting, and gzip compression.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>nginx</tag>
      <tag>reverse-proxy</tag>
      <tag>load-balancing</tag>
      <tag>tls</tag>
      <tag>web-server</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Nginx Configuration</title>

    <summary>Nginx as high-performance HTTP server, reverse proxy, and load balancer. Key production requirements: TLS 1.2/1.3 only, server_tokens off, all security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options), rate limiting, and gzip compression. Always test with nginx -t before reload.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Misconfigured Nginx is the most common vector for information leakage (version in headers), clickjacking, and MITM attacks. A properly configured instance achieves SSL Labs A+ grade with zero extra cost and handles 400k-500k req/s at cluster scale. TLS 1.0/1.1 must be disabled; Let's Encrypt deprecated OCSP in August 2025.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Serving static sites or SPA frontends with aggressive cache headers</item>
        <item>Reverse proxying backend services with proper X-Forwarded-* headers</item>
        <item>SSL/TLS termination with Let's Encrypt certificates</item>
        <item>Load balancing across multiple upstream backends</item>
        <item>Rate limiting login/API endpoints to prevent brute-force</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Dynamic application logic — Nginx is a proxy, not an app server</item>
        <item>Complex routing rules that require request body inspection — use Envoy or Traefik</item>
        <item>Kubernetes ingress at scale — use a dedicated ingress controller (nginx-ingress, Traefik)</item>
        <item>Service mesh traffic management — that's Istio/Linkerd territory</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="worker-and-connection-settings">
      <p>Worker and connection settings optimize Nginx for production workloads. Set worker_processes to auto and worker_connections to 4096 or higher for production servers.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set worker_processes to auto and worker_connections to 4096 or higher for production servers.</statement>
        <rationale>auto matches CPU core count. Each worker handles worker_connections simultaneous connections; 4096 supports high-traffic workloads without tuning per server type.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Worker and Connection Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
worker_processes auto;
events {
    worker_connections 4096;
    use epoll;
    multi_accept on;
}
http {
    sendfile        on;
    tcp_nopush      on;
    tcp_nodelay     on;
    keepalive_timeout 65;
    types_hash_max_size 2048;
    server_tokens   off;
}
        ]]></code>
        <note>tcp_nopush requires sendfile on. server_tokens off hides the Nginx version from response headers.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="gzip-compression">
      <p>Gzip compression reduces bandwidth consumption. Enable gzip for all text content types with comp_level 6 and min_length 256.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable gzip for all text content types with comp_level 6 and min_length 256. Always include gzip_vary on.</statement>
        <rationale>Level 6 gives the best compression-to-CPU ratio. min_length 256 avoids compressing tiny responses where overhead exceeds gain. gzip_vary ensures proxies cache both compressed and uncompressed variants.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Gzip Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
gzip              on;
gzip_vary         on;
gzip_proxied      any;
gzip_comp_level   6;
gzip_min_length   256;
gzip_types
    text/plain text/css text/xml text/javascript
    application/json application/javascript application/xml
    application/rss+xml image/svg+xml;
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="tls-configuration">
      <p>TLS configuration ensures encrypted connections with modern protocols. Allow TLSv1.2 and TLSv1.3 only. Disable session tickets. Use ssl_session_cache shared.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Allow TLSv1.2 and TLSv1.3 only. Disable session tickets. Use ssl_session_cache shared. Let's Encrypt no longer supports OCSP (deprecated August 2025) — remove ssl_stapling directives.</statement>
        <rationale>TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are deprecated by RFC 8996 and fail PCI DSS compliance. ssl_session_tickets off prevents reuse of session keys that compromise forward secrecy. OCSP stapling is now unsupported by Let's Encrypt.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="TLS 1.2/1.3 Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
ssl_protocols       TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
ssl_ciphers         ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;
ssl_prefer_server_ciphers off;
ssl_session_cache   shared:SSL:10m;
ssl_session_timeout 1d;
ssl_session_tickets off;
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Deprecated TLS Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
ssl_protocols TLSv1 TLSv1.1 TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;  # TLS 1.0/1.1 deprecated
ssl_stapling on;  # Unsupported since Let's Encrypt dropped OCSP (Aug 2025)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="security-headers">
      <p>Security headers protect against multiple attack classes. Add all five required security headers to every HTTPS server block: HSTS, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy, and Permissions-Policy.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Add all five required security headers to every HTTPS server block: HSTS, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy, and Permissions-Policy.</statement>
        <rationale>Each header mitigates a specific attack class: HSTS forces HTTPS, X-Frame-Options prevents clickjacking, X-Content-Type-Options prevents MIME sniffing, Referrer-Policy limits information leakage, Permissions-Policy disables unneeded browser APIs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Security Headers">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains" always;
add_header X-Frame-Options           "SAMEORIGIN"                          always;
add_header X-Content-Type-Options    "nosniff"                             always;
add_header Referrer-Policy           "strict-origin-when-cross-origin"     always;
add_header Permissions-Policy        "geolocation=(), microphone=(), camera=()" always;
        ]]></code>
        <note>Use always to include headers in error responses, not just 200 OK.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="reverse-proxy">
      <p>Reverse proxy setup requires proper header forwarding. Always pass X-Forwarded-For, X-Forwarded-Proto, X-Real-IP, and Host headers when proxying.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always pass X-Forwarded-For, X-Forwarded-Proto, X-Real-IP, and Host headers when proxying. Set proxy_read_timeout and proxy_connect_timeout explicitly.</statement>
        <rationale>Without these headers, the backend application cannot determine the client's real IP or whether the original request was HTTP or HTTPS — critical for security logging and redirect logic.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/proxy-params.conf">Reusable proxy params snippet</reference>
      <example type="good" title="Reverse Proxy Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
# /etc/nginx/snippets/proxy-params.conf
proxy_set_header Host               $host;
proxy_set_header X-Real-IP          $remote_addr;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For    $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto  $scheme;
proxy_http_version                  1.1;
proxy_connect_timeout               60s;
proxy_send_timeout                  60s;
proxy_read_timeout                  60s;
proxy_buffering                     on;
proxy_buffer_size                   4k;
proxy_buffers                       8 4k;

# In server block:
location / {
    include snippets/proxy-params.conf;
    proxy_pass http://backend;
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="load-balancing">
      <p>Load balancing distributes traffic across upstream servers. Use least_conn for API backends where request duration varies.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use least_conn for API backends where request duration varies. Use ip_hash only when sticky sessions are required and session-level state cannot be externalized.</statement>
        <rationale>Round-robin distributes requests evenly but sends long requests to already-busy servers. least_conn routes to the server with fewest active connections, producing more even load in heterogeneous workloads. ip_hash creates an uneven distribution when clients are behind NAT.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Load Balancing Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
upstream backend {
    least_conn;
    server backend1.example.com:8080;
    server backend2.example.com:8080;
    server backend3.example.com:8080;
    keepalive 32;          # Reuse upstream connections
}
upstream backend_ha {
    server backend1.example.com:8080 max_fails=3 fail_timeout=30s;
    server backend2.example.com:8080 max_fails=3 fail_timeout=30s;
    server backup.example.com:8080   backup;
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="websocket-support">
      <p>WebSocket proxying requires connection upgrade. Set Upgrade and Connection headers explicitly; set proxy_read_timeout to at least 3600s for long-lived connections.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>WebSocket proxying requires upgrading the connection. Set Upgrade and Connection headers explicitly; set proxy_read_timeout to at least 3600s for long-lived connections.</statement>
        <rationale>HTTP/1.1 WebSocket upgrades use the Upgrade header. Without Connection: upgrade, Nginx drops the connection. Short proxy_read_timeout kills idle WebSocket connections.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="WebSocket Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
location /ws/ {
    proxy_pass         http://websocket_backend;
    proxy_http_version 1.1;
    proxy_set_header   Upgrade    $http_upgrade;
    proxy_set_header   Connection "upgrade";
    proxy_read_timeout 3600s;
    proxy_send_timeout 3600s;
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="rate-limiting">
      <p>Rate limiting protects against brute-force and DDoS attacks. Define rate limit zones in http{} block and apply limit_req with burst and nodelay to sensitive endpoints.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define rate limit zones in http{} block. Apply limit_req with burst and nodelay to sensitive endpoints (login, API keys, password reset).</statement>
        <rationale>Zones defined once and referenced in multiple locations. nodelay serves burst requests immediately rather than queuing them, preventing legitimate users from seeing delays during momentary traffic spikes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Rate Limiting Configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
# In http {} block:
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=login:10m rate=5r/m;
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api:10m    rate=100r/s;
limit_conn_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=addr:10m;

# In server {} location:
location /api/auth/login {
    limit_req zone=login burst=3 nodelay;
    limit_req_status 429;
    proxy_pass http://backend;
}
location /api/ {
    limit_req  zone=api burst=50 nodelay;
    limit_conn addr 20;
    proxy_pass http://backend;
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="configuration-syntax-check">
      <p>Nginx configuration syntax validation is critical before reload. Run nginx -t before every reload or deploy.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run nginx -t before every reload or deploy. Never reload without passing -t — a broken config silently keeps the old config running but the next reload will fail.</statement>
        <rationale>nginx -t validates syntax and checks include paths without restarting. On managed systems, an invalid config on reload can leave the server running stale configuration for hours until noticed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Configuration Validation">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
sudo nginx -t && sudo nginx -s reload
# Or on systemd:
sudo nginx -t && sudo systemctl reload nginx
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="security-checklist">
      <p>Security checklist ensures all critical security requirements are met before going live.</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>server_tokens off in http{} block — verify with curl -I and check for Server: nginx/x.x header absence</check>
        <check>TLS 1.2 and 1.3 only — verify: openssl s_client -connect host:443 and check Protocol field</check>
        <check>All five security headers present — verify with curl -I or securityheaders.com</check>
        <check>HSTS max-age at least 31536000 (1 year) for public sites</check>
        <check>SSL session tickets disabled (ssl_session_tickets off)</check>
        <check>DH parameters file generated if using custom ciphers (openssl dhparam -out /etc/nginx/dhparam.pem 2048)</check>
        <check>HTTP to HTTPS redirect: 301 not 302 for permanent redirect</check>
        <check>File permissions: config files 644, SSL private keys 600, owned by root</check>
        <check>Deny access to .git, .env, and sensitive paths with location ~ /\. { deny all; }</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="ssl-tls-validation">
      <p>SSL/TLS validation ensures proper certificate configuration and security. Run SSL Labs test for every new domain and aim for A+ grade.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run SSL Labs test (ssllabs.com/ssltest) for every new domain. Aim for A+ grade. Resolve any warnings before going live.</statement>
        <rationale>SSL Labs checks protocol versions, cipher strength, certificate chain, HSTS, and 40+ other criteria. A+ grade means all current best practices are met and no known vulnerabilities are present.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="SSL/TLS Validation Commands">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Quick local SSL check
echo | openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -noout -dates

# Check certificate chain validity
curl -sI https://example.com | grep -E 'HTTP|Strict|X-Frame|X-Content'

# Verify TLS version
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -tls1 2>&1 | grep -E 'Protocol|Cipher'
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="performance-and-compression-checklist">
      <p>Performance and compression checklist ensures optimal throughput and response times.</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>Gzip enabled and returning Content-Encoding: gzip for text responses: curl -H "Accept-Encoding: gzip" -I https://example.com</check>
        <check>Static assets served with far-future cache headers (expires max or Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000)</check>
        <check>Keepalive working: verify via curl -v --http1.1 and check for Connection: keep-alive in response</check>
        <check>Upstream keepalive configured (keepalive 32 in upstream block) to avoid per-request TCP handshakes to backend</check>
        <check>worker_processes auto and worker_connections 4096+ in nginx.conf</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="reverse-proxy-checklist">
      <p>Reverse proxy checklist for production deployments using Nginx as a proxy.</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>proxy_pass URL has no trailing slash if location has no trailing slash (avoid double-slash bugs)</check>
        <check>X-Forwarded-For set using $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for (not $remote_addr alone)</check>
        <check>Proxy timeouts match backend service SLA (proxy_read_timeout, proxy_send_timeout)</check>
        <check>Health check endpoint responds correctly through Nginx</check>
        <check>WebSocket locations have Upgrade and Connection headers if applicable</check>
        <check>Rate limiting applied to auth and sensitive API endpoints</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="post-deploy-validation">
      <p>Post-deploy validation ensures all systems are working correctly in production.</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>All routes return expected HTTP status codes</check>
        <check>HTTP to HTTPS redirect works (301, not redirect loop)</check>
        <check>Certificate expiry monitoring configured (alert at 30 days before expiry)</check>
        <check>stub_status endpoint accessible from monitoring only, not public</check>
        <check>Error log level set to warn (not debug) in production</check>
        <check>Log rotation configured (logrotate.d or systemd log rotation)</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/ssl-params.conf" purpose="TLS protocol/cipher/session snippet (include in server blocks)"/>
      <template path="templates/security-headers.conf" purpose="HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy snippet"/>
      <template path="templates/proxy-params.conf" purpose="Proxy headers, timeouts, buffering snippet"/>
      <template path="templates/static-site.conf" purpose="Full static site vhost with HTTPS redirect and cache headers"/>
      <template path="templates/reverse-proxy.conf" purpose="Full reverse proxy vhost template"/>
      <template path="templates/rate-limit.conf" purpose="Rate limiting zones and location-level directives"/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://nginx.org/en/docs/"/>
      <link href="https://www.ssllabs.com/ssltest/"/>
      <link href="https://securityheaders.com/"/>
      <link href="https://cipherlist.eu/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
